- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
a little late to the party but..
--
happy international men's day! ğŸ’•ğŸ‰ğŸ™ŒğŸ¾â™‚ï¸ in the midst of #metoo #thefutureisfemale and other social trends i want to give a shout out to all the men doing their best in a society which paints their gender with the same brush. not all men are trash.

shout out to the men who do not let the pain of their past and present dictate and determin their mistreatment of others. to the men who strive to be emotionally healthy and sew the seeds of love where ever they go.

shout out to all the present fathers. not just physically and financially but emotionally too. even if you're no longer with the mother of your child/children, you still show up and show out for your children because you realise that being a parent is bigger than you and "baby mama drama" (shout out to the single fathers doing it alone too) .

shout out to all the guys who are amazing friends to both each other and females. to the amazing husbands, boyfriends, fiancÃ©s, brothers, sons, cousins and uncles. to the guys who build up those around them. to the guys reaching out to youngers in their communities and families, providing mentorship and guidance.

shout out to the guys who may not have it all together but remain determined to get better with each day. you may not have two pennies to rub together or have issues to work through but kingdoms were not built over night, keep pressing on. not everyone is destined to be the next bill gates and it's ok if you don't achieve all your goals. you're human.

shout out to all the men of god who put our father at the forefront of everything they do in life. its not easy being a man of god in a world which has destorted what manhood should look like. your integrity is priceless.

and to my women- it is not anti-female to celebrate men. don't let popular culture and life make you jaded and bitter. for every "scum bag" and "scoundrel" you may come across there is indeed a large abundance of phenomenal men in the world, and they deserve our appreciation ğŸ‘ğŸ¾ğŸ™ŒğŸ¾. #internationalmensday #men #love #relationshipgoals #relationships #christianblogger #celebration #blogger #manhood

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr

text:
i'm closer to the golden dawn
immersed in crowley's uniform
of imagery
i'm living in a silent film
portraying himmler's sacred realm
of dream reality
i'm frightened by the total goal
drawing to the ragged hole
and i ain't got the power anymore
no, i ain't got the power anymore

i'm the twisted name on garbo's eyes
living proof of churchill's lies, i'm destiny
i'm torn between the light and dark
where others see their targets, divine symmetry
should i kiss the viper's fang?
or herald loud the death of man

i'm sinking in the quicksand of my thought
and i ain't got the power anymore

don't believe in yourself
don't deceive with belief
knowledge comes with death's release
aah-aah, aah-aah, aah-aah, aah-aah

i'm not a prophet or a stone-age man
just a mortal with the potential of a superman
i'm living on
i'm tethered to the logic of homo sapien
can't take my eyes from the great salvation
of bullshit faith
if i don't explain what you ought to know
you can tell me all about it on the next bardo

i'm sinking in the quicksand of my thought
and i ain't got the power anymore

don't believe in yourself
don't deceive with belief
knowledge comes with death's release
aah-aah, aah-aah, aah-aah, aah-aah

david bowie

.
the case has parallels with a trial in scotland in 2002 in which a 15-year-old boy was found guilty of raping 17-year-old girl who was forced to hold up her underwear in court three times. she committed suicide two weeks after the court case.
.
this is fucking outrageous, and we have no words to describe how appalled we are by this.

text:
me in #metoo is coming back to you mumbai! 
we @doctordramatherapy understand that embracing your story is easier said than done. me in #metoo is a drama therapy workshop for survivors of physical and emotional trauma. a closed group workshop with not more than 5-8 people that will focus on:

1. identifying and disembodying trauma as it sits in the body
2. celebrating the survivor in you 
3. embodying your strength through story-telling and psychodrama

it is important to give yourself a safe space to heal just like you have found a space to bravely express your individual stories. know someone who needs this space then do share this post with them. 
pre-register before 30th november and avail of a 10% discount on the workshop. 
call us at 8850860728 or email me @ doctordramatherapy@gmail.com

share. heal. grow with a touch of drama for therapy at doctor drama this friday (30th november)
venue: the little game bay
time: 6:30-8pm

as carrie fischer would say, "take your broken heart, make it into art." follow us on facebook for more updates. 
https://www.facebook.com/events/2281064288840732/ .

text:
beneath the veil - cover reveal

i am so excited to reveal the cover of my next book, 'beneath the veil' which will be released in early february 2019. 
@natashagilmoureditorial and i are deep in the editing process, an experience i absolutely love as we work together so beautifully in refining the shared vision we have for this very special book.

in response to some frequently asked questions:

1. no, it is not a sequel to let's go home, finding there while staying here.

2. yes, it is another work of fiction with powerful healing and spiritual growth themes.

3. yes, i am as excited about sharing 'beneath the veil' with you as i was sharing let's go home.

4. no, it is not based on any of my clients, family or friends, although it is based in rural ireland in a strict catholic village - so i may have some strong ancestral ties to the story without being consciously aware of my ancestors stories.

5. yes, i adore my central characters - clara and maeve, and i am so grateful that they chose me to share their story with the world. they are powerful women who you will learn so much from - i know both @natashagilmoureditorial and i have learnt much already from these wise souls.

6. yes, you can pre-order from january 2019 - i'll keep you posted.

its hard to express how grateful i am for the support i feel as i bring my books into the world. 
thanks to @majaotic for yet another amazing cover design (i love your work and you!) @ljminto for being my #1 supporter in everything i do and to @nourishment4soul for holding space for me as i wrote this one - she is big. 
and to @karenmcdermottpublisher who is walking the publishing path again with me, thank you for guiding me xx

[trigger warning]

in 2002, 17 year old lindsay armstrong of scotland took her own life two weeks after she was forced to show her thong and read out the slogan printed on the front reading â€œlittle devilâ€ in a rape trial. this had nothing to do with the case, and lindsay was forced to hold up her underwear three times. itâ€™s been 16 years. when will we stop humiliating and degrading the victim? when will we truly start to understand the trauma of rape and stop trying to acquit monsters? there are so many parallels between this case and the case in ireland (see previous post) that spurred outrage online and throughout the world. we need to see change. soon.

disclaimer:
i mean no disrespect to the armstrong family and am only trying to spread awareness. if any member or friend would like this post removed, please dm me.

text:
armenia is going toÂ liberalize the visa regime with india. the draft of the relevantÂ resolution is included in the agenda of the government meeting onÂ  november 16.
according to the draft, citizens of india will be able to obtain aÂ  visa at the entrance to armenia in accordance with the procedureÂ  approved by the ra government on october 4, 2007 - at borderÂ  checkpoints, on the electronic visa system or in diplomatic missionsÂ  and consulates in foreign countries. Â as stated in the certificate ofÂ  support to the document, the draft decision is aimed at liberalizingÂ  visa relations with india, including on a reciprocal basis. based onÂ  the results of the decision, the growth of the tourist flow toÂ  armenia from india, as well as the volume of mutual trade andÂ  investment, is expected. for january-september of 2017, compared withÂ  the same period last year, the number of tourists from india toÂ  armenia increased by 168%. from january 1 to august 31, the armenianÂ  embassy in india provided 1695 entry visas, which is 479 more than inÂ  the same period of 2016.
"this decision comes into force on the day following the day of itsÂ  official publication, and extends to legal relations that have arisenÂ  since november 22, 2017," the draft resolution says.

text:
women are fierce forces to be reckoned with. god created woman strong and brave. bold and strong. kind and gentle. we encompass beauty.  yet we live in a culture that looks to distort that beauty. to distort our dignity and worth. we live in a culture that looks to rob and destroy woman. to bring us down. but our god is good and i refuse to listen to the lies; to allow this culture to bring me down. because i was created strong and brave. because i believe that if i am fully a woman, fully and fearfully myself, this culture will change. i will be a part of that change. because i believe that this culture can and will change. ladies, let us not let this culture keep us down anymore. let us be the moving forces that create a culture where our dignity and worth is seen and upheld. #metoo â €
â €
bianca herrera
name: The Culture Project Intl

text:
aksi solidaritas untuk agni dan ibu nuril
.
"bungkam saja yang ingin bicara. kebebasan hanya tuk yang berkuasa," tutur si holong lewat lagu ciptaan nostress.
.
agni yang diperkosa oleh rekan se-kkn dan ibu nuril yang dilecehkan oleh atasannya adalah hanya sedikit dari banyaknya kasus kekerasan terhadap perempuan di muka bumi ini. aksi solidaritas yang kami persembahkan bagi korban ketidakadilan ini semoga bisa mengajak kita semua sedar bahwa ketidakadilan ini mesti dihentikan. segera. sekarang juga.
.

text:
so you touched them uncomfortably, sneered while looking at them lecherously, harassed them but then you dug a graveyard and burried all the your blemishes and sin so asto come clean. all the while, did you realise that you didn't just bury your erroneous deeds but also burried a living carcass of a person dying every day? now with a spark of #metoo all your revelations are being exposed to the world. don't worry, the carcasses have the  prowess in getting burried, this time they'll bury their anguishes and pain with the advent of the movement.
'me too' campaign gained significance as early as 2006 with tarana burke, an american social activist's incessant use in public speeches. it gained existence over  the social media platforms in 2017 with american actress, alyssa milano using it as a hashtag in her tweet.
it spread out like fire across the world as expected and people across the globe who have had been the victims of the sexual exploitation by their co-workers, office staff etc began to use this hashtag.
people from various fields, be it cinematography or corporal world, sports or media world came out strong and popularised the hashtag, making it public that they have faced it in the past, have overcome it and are now so strong that they can even discuss about it on the social media. this shows the unassailable will that  the victims carry, that they don't feel intimidated anymore. it's just the beginning, only a few lit candles  have come out from the cavern. many more will come from their dark pasts to send the sinners to where they deserve to be. always remember, escape isn't easy, neither it is for the sinners nor the ones who are suffering from the trauma inflicted upon them. #aaghaaz #womenempowerment #raiseyourvoice #metoo #metooindia

text:
enroute to a discussion on power, privilege and oppression in the emerging coaching space. like other professions, coaching is facing questions about who coaches, who has access to coaching and how we can do a better job of expanding our understanding and approaches to include and meet the  needs of a broader group of people. most recently, the association of coach training organizations (acto) took a stand in addressing power, privilege and oppression (ppo) in the coach education field. 
in an era of #metoo, black lives matter and truth and reconciliation, as coaches we need safe and brave spaces to explore who we are as coaches, unpack our own power and privilege, reflect on our biases, and their impact on our clients, and take steps to strengthen our competency in this area. #cafelife #lifecoaching #lifecoach #privilege #oppression #lifeonpurpose #morningjoe #espresso #firstwind #metoo #blacklivesmatter #reconciliation #coaching #socialchange #changeagent

text:
my name is trina.
i try.
too hard sometimes.
because i might not be good at it right away,
and i know i am still struggling to overcome my past, so who am i to speak encouragement? 
i know someone needs to hear that the circumstances we are born into do not define us. 
the mistakes we've made don't have to derail the entirety of our life

we can forgive.
we can love. 
we can find peace. 
we can overcome.

#metoo #heisfaithful #nottodaysatan

text:
pre-holiday tip 5...pay attention!!!...
as your family gathers for the holidays, be aware of how your child responds to family and friends. if they tense up, cry, becomes clearly agitated or fearful, grabs you or moves to safety, or leaves when someone enters the room, this can be an indicator that your child has had an adverse experience with this individual. many children who are being or have been sexually abused will not openly disclose what has occurred, especially when it involves family members and close family friends; however, their body language and behavior will speak volumes about how they feel about an individual. keep in mind that this pertains to their response to other children as well, because children sexually abuse other children and some of the same power dynamics associated with adult abusers are used to enforce silence and compliance in peer sex abuse. if you notice this sudden change in body language, mood, or behavior, take a moment to privately discuss your child's response to this person and if you're still unsure about your child's explanation, take measures to keep your child isolated from this individual until you can investigate further. remember, you don't need permission to protect your child and you can cut off a person's access to your child at anytime with no explanation required. be aware of changes in mood and behavior leading up to the time you're scheduled to attend a family gathering. also, if you notice sudden outbursts of crying or anger, sadness, depression, anxiety, inability to sleep or nightmares, bed wetting or loss of appetite during the days leading up to a family function, talk to your child about what they're feeling and if it involves your upcoming family gathering. a "child" is any person under the age of 18, so our tips apply to children of all ages. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

i replaced my smoothie routine with lemon peel water.

this is warm lemon water with fresh honey from the beehive and 3 whole lemon peels minced.

i normally add lime and do the same thing with lime juice and lime skin, but i ran out.

many people toss the lemon skin out and just drink the lemon juice but the meat and potatoes of the benefits are in the skin itself.

if you drink warm lemon and lime juice with lemon and lime peels for breakfast and dinner everyday for one month, you will feel 10 years younger at the end of that month.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

text:
//
my love,
my pain,
if you ever come back one day,
a long, long time from now,
i'm not sure what i'd say.
so much effort i've spent,
time i've wasted,
days and nights,
sun and moon,
all pass by as i try to forget you.
so if one day you come back,
i don't know what i'd do.
would i open the door again?
let you in, greet you with warmth?
i loved you,
i still do,
but if you ever come back,
it would be a long,
long time from now.
and it's a strange feeling,
that i hope and pray,
for this love in my heart,
this flame for you,
to never burn away,
never die,
never fade.
but at the same time
i frantically try,
try to smoother it,
suffocate it,
crush it back into the
depths if oblivion.
or,
would i turn you away,
as i probably should?
slam that door,
turn my shoulder,
and walk away for good?
such a day,
should it ever come to be,
is far,
far away.
but i think,
i know,
that i would probably
open that door,
unable to turn you away,
too caught up by you,
strung up in your web.
how could i push you away,
when i still love you?
or maybe,
maybe we could simply start over.
several years from now,
we'd be different,
we'd be changed people,
maybe it could begin again.
or not.
it's not good to hold onto hope.
we shouldn't love the ones
who hurt us,
even though sometimes
we can't help it.
so my love,
i have to let you go.
but if you ever come back,
.
.
well...
maybe,

maybe.
.
.
ananya sharma.
(@afflictionwrites)
.
.

that i hope and pray,
for this love in my heart,
this flame for you,
to never burn away,
never die,
never fade.
but at the same time
i frantically try,
try to smoother it,
suffocate it,
crush it back into the
depths if oblivion.
or,
would i turn you away,
as i probably should?
slam that door,
turn my shoulder,
and walk away for good?
such a day,
should it ever come to be,
is far,
far away.
but i think,
i know,
that i would probably
open that door,
unable to turn you away,
too caught up by you,
strung up in your web.
how could i push you away,
when i still love you?
or maybe,
maybe we could simply start over.
several years from now,
we'd be different,
we'd be changed people,
maybe it could begin again.
or not.
it is not good to hold onto hope.
we should not love the ones
who hurt us,
even though sometimes
we can not help it.
so my love,
i have to let you go.
but if you ever come back,
.
.
well...
maybe,

maybe.
.
.
aya sharma.

the north yorkshire force had said it was looking for a "fat, naked man" and described his sexual organs explicitly after the incident onÂ sunday afternoon.

it said the appeal had "caused upset to a number of people". the details on its website have now been replaced with a "more appropriately worded version". more stories from around yorkshire

the revised wording, which was also posted to its facebook page, removed the detailed description of the man's "small penis" and "testicles that hang noticeably low". how is it offensive to describe 50% of our sex organs? and most of the other 50% will have seen more balls than the 50^ who have them.

it's like a female thinking she can speak with .ore authority about breasts than a good few men. keep dreaming.

and why post it? i think it's not hard to find a naked fat man with a small... wondering about. 
isn't fat the most offensive word anyway?

it's not even necessarily a true story. in fact on the balance of probability of say the crying shame is it's more likely fabricated. ğŸ˜‘ğŸ˜¯ how about since they are in yorkshire; they get out those files on parliamentary and lords child abuse that theresa suppressed.

text:
"top n.h. court upholds labrieâ€™s convictions in sex assault on girlâ€ "the new hampshire supreme court on tuesday upheld the convictions of owen labrie, the former st. paulâ€™s student found guilty in 2015 of sexually assaulting a 15-year-old girl in a room on campus the year before and using a computer to lure her into the encounter.

labrieâ€™s convictions were affirmed by a 3-0 vote.

labrie, now 23, was acquitted at trial of raping the victim, chessy prout, who was also enrolled at st. paulâ€™s at the time of the incident, but he was convicted of misdemeanor sexual assault for having sex with someone below the age of consent and using computer services to entice a minor. the computer charge was a felony conviction and triggered a requirement that he register as a sex offender. labrie had communicated electronically with prout to set up their meeting.

in a statement, proutâ€™s parents welcomed tuesdayâ€™s ruling. â€œthe past four years in this process have been long and grueling for our daughter . . . ,â€™â€™ the statement said. â€œwe applaud our daughterâ€™s courage in shattering the silence and persisting through a long and difficult fight for justice. chessy and our entire family are committed to encouraging other survivors to seek help and support to help them find their path for justice and healing.â€™â€™ her parents also thanked the prosecutors who worked the case, noting that they demonstrated â€œprofessionalism and courageâ€™â€™ in seeking justice for prout, â€œlong before the widespread support of #metoo, or the many other cases which have since come to light at st. paulâ€™s school.â€™â€™ â€œthe computer felony law, as now interpreted by the n.h. supreme court, can ensnare any senior in high school who communicates through their phone, tablet, or laptop with a freshman in high school and invites them on a date,â€™â€™ rancourt said.she called on state lawmakers to â€œfix this terribly flawed law.â€™â€™ prout has gone public with her ordeal and published a searing memoir, written with boston globe reporter jenn abelson, entitled â€œi have the right to: a high school survivorâ€™s story of sexual assault, justice, and hope.â€™â€™ â¤ï¸ source: by travis anderson & john r. ellement, globe staff

labrie, now 23, was acquitted at trial of raping the victim, chessy prout, who was also enrolled at st. paulâ€™s at the time of the incident, but he was convicted of misdemeanor sexual assault for having sex with someone below the age of consent and using computer services to entice a minor. the computer charge was a felony conviction and triggered a requirement that he register as a sex offender. labrie had communicated electronically with prout to set up their meeting.

in many cultures, rape was not considered a sexual crime against a particular woman but as a theft/insult against her â€œownerâ€ or against her chastity. the rape of a virgin girl was considered a more serious crime than that of a non-virgin. and the rape of a sex worker, slave or an â€œunchasteâ€ woman was in some laws not considered a crime because it was believed that she had no chastity that could be damaged. â €
â €
â €
centuries later it was still believed by many that women who expose their body image publicly, as is the case of dancers, models, performers and actresses, have no chastity or decency left to be defended by the law.â €
â €

text:
part of the nyc commission on human rights mission is to inform new yorkers on their rights and responsibilities under the human rights law.  this year, in response to the #metoo and #timesup movements, we rolled out a workplace #sexualharassment campaign with a clear message: it's not just flirting, a hug, or a joke - it's sexual harassment!

we are proud to announce that our campaign received a gold award from @marcom_awards and a @shortyawards nomination.  kudos to our campaign partners vanguard and killer content. thank you for the recognition as we continue our outreach to ensure all new yorkers know their rights!

visit our campaign page at bit.ly/sh-nyc

text:
come, sit beside me

tell me how do i look, 
too tired or too plastic?

look into my eyes, 
do they look too dry 
or do they look like
they're still holding 
an ocean more of tears behind them

run your finger over my wrinkled heart, 
which has become too old, too early, 
hold it, i say, hold it carefully
and tell me, 
does it weigh heavy? is it still carrying the weight of those sulky memories

run your fingers through my skin and feel the scars, 
do they still weep over the stories which died few years ago? 
or are they dying to breathe? 
swallow my fears, and tell me how they taste, like my experiences or regrets

hug me and see, do my arms have any energy left, to hold someone tight, close and safe? 
look at my hands, do they look like they're still willing to hold other? or they still look young?

look at my lips, do they look like they have much to say, or they've surrendered to the numbness that the heart carries?

for once, listen to my silence, and tell me, does it still scream or it has given up?

come, sit beside me 
and tell me how do i look? 
do i look tired, 
or am i still good at faking it?
~ kalyani kulkarni

text:
about the creative process of playwright @argiacoppolaâ€™s stage adaptation of blonde, the pulitzer prize finalist novel by @joycecaroloates.

in this extract from her interview with @corriere corriere della sera, la lettura (november 17th, 2017), @argiacoppola talks about the intimate connection she feels with marilyn, and the importance of her life story:

marilyn uses her imagination to change reality and to react to pain in an unexpected way. i felt an immediate connection, and in that moment, i decided that her story was an important one to tell for women today; that she was a misunderstood woman, never got (as is often the case for women), different from what the world believed. i was happy to discover, during a recent dinner with oates, that she thought of it the same way. when i read the first words of her novel, â€œand then came deathâ€¦â€ i understood that i would not have been able to write a new text without this novel. i feel a profound gratitude to this great author for having written such an extensive, powerful, complex work.â€ _______________

want to delve deeper into our world? keep following, and discover our #crowdfunding now running on the #linkinbio. contribute any way you can: every dollar counts! if we donâ€™t reach the final amount, we wonâ€™t keep any donation made, and our dream of taking marilynâ€™s untold truth to broadway will be halted.

text: i am so thrilled to share a project with you all that just came out in this month's elle magazine. this summer i had the great privilege to photograph 12 courageous and inspiring women for elle. this project, titled 'the replacements' is a series of portraits outstanding women who have taken over the jobs of men who were outed during the #metoo movement. spanning from hollywood to politics and beyond, these women have boldly ascended. as both a woman and a photographer i could not be more proud to have been chosen to shoot this project- i am humbled and inspired. thank you  thank you lauren, martin, and katelyn. you three nothing short of incredible. thank you to all of the amazingly gifted stylists, hair and makeup artists, and assistants who worked so hard on this project. you all are gold. thank you violet o'neill and oliphant studios for your generosity and support. @laurenwbrown @katelynmbaker @anatolli @campbellritchie @elleusa @ninagarcia @robingwright @sarahschussheim @kendalmaeboyle @riadazar9 @maggiebullock @oliphantstudio @violet_ohoh @spyderman31 @aprilblumphoto

text: i have been absent from not only social media lately but a lot of other aspects of my life. i know it was for a good cause though. the last two weekends i was given yet another opportunity to partake in the #metoo survivor circle stories. i donâ€™t think i realized what it would feel like for me to tell me story that many times. i am exhausted, vulnerable, and thankful for the opportunity. i know the value of speaking of my story and speaking my truth. but i also know it feels like very intensive exposure therapy as the cast came to deem it. and it has truly caused some shifts in my thinking. that what happened to me was not a scene from a movie but a real life experience. it has been hard for me to come to this realization. to realize i am human and mortal and during that portion of time i was in a life or death situation. so thank you to my survivors sisters who were with me during this process and gave me their shoulders to cry on, thank you to my fiancÃ© for just staying home with me when i needed it, and thank you to playbuilders for giving me this opportunity. #metoo #hawaii #playbuilders #survivor #survivorstories

text:
â¬‡ï¸what i learned from taking risks â¬‡ï¸
ğŸ’¢
i used to be a "box checker." society made these goals and i was gona acheive them! get my diploma, checkâœ”get my degree, checkâœ”! land my career that is a result of my degree, check!! âœ”
ğŸ’¢
but then... my job didn't make me happy. and the job after that didn't make me happy either. i felt like a failure. why could everyone find and keep a job for 30+ years and retire? yet no matter how many times i moved, i wasnt happy.
ğŸ’¢
each time i found that i was internally unhappy, i recognized that i was not following my soul, my purpose. and each time i felt uneasy, i found the courage to let go and move!!!
ğŸ’¢
eventually, i realized that i had been living up to what was expected of me, rather than following my own calling and purpose. but i also discovered that each time i made a courageous change to a new job, i felt better! ğŸ’¢
i continued to take baby steps and follow my inner voice to what felt right to me. ğŸ’¢
i refused to stay at a job because it was the most money i'd ever made. my happiness came first. i didn't settle for a place with people that did not respect and appreciate me. i chose to put myself and my happiness first!
ğŸ’¢
taking risks is scary, but i can promise that no matter how it turns out, it is always worth it. you will always find yourself just a little (if not a whole lot) closer to what your calling is; your soul's purpose. your joy!
ğŸ’¢
quit that job you dread going to, find a better one! dabble in activities you enjoy and explore how you can make a career out of your passion! take that class you're interested in. whatever it is, go!!!
ğŸ’¢
as long as you feel that longing inside, it is your soul nudging you to move and follow your heart. it is for a reason.
ğŸ’¢
you'll never grow if you don't move. and as long as you're taking steps towards your happiness, you're growing! that's the beauty of itğŸŒ±ğŸ’œ
ğŸ’¢

text:
god first the rest will followâ€¦ğŸ’œ
.
how many times have i read those words? it wasnâ€™t untilÂ iÂ learned this truth, when i really dissected it and took it apart to put it back togetherâ€¦.i was able to breathe a sigh of relief.
.
not just at having received such a revelation but to step out & put it into practice. you see i had become a control â€˜freakâ€™. i figured if i can control the situation, if i can control this person, if i can control the outcomeâ€¦control thisâ€¦control thatâ€¦do you see how exhausting it is just reading that sentence?! yikes!
.
i was really putting myself first. granted it came from a deep rooted place of fear, self-hatred, anxiety, & vulnerability. it was my way of protecting myself from past traumas. the more i tried to control things, the less i could control. being in a constant state of tense fight or flight mode is no way to live.
.
â€˜for god has not given us a spirit of fear and timidity, but of power, love, and self-discipline.â€˜ 2 timothy 1:7 . -this has become one of my power verses. it gives me strength when i feel myself slipping back into that dark place.
.
i have gradually made it a consistent practice to begin each day at 5am meditating on the word in quiet reflection. it is the only time my mind is quiet and undistracted.
.
throughout the day i have to continually look to god first and know in faith that the rest will follow.
.
 it will be a lifetime of perfecting this practice so that it is ingrained in my very being. it is the first step to recovery and i am on my way!
.
i pray that you will be encouraged today. we are all  #hisworkinprogress !ğŸ¦‹
.
.
.
w/love

text:
consent has nothing to do with clothing! .

consistently victims of sexual assault are being let down. 
victims of sexual assaults are often asked what they did/said/wore to provoke an attack. 
as a society we are being told what we should do to prevent attacks rather than telling those committing the crime not to do it in the first place. .

what a person is or is not wearing does not give anyone the right to take advantage. 
using a person's clothing choice against them the justify rape is appalling. 
for people to fear attacks, not just because of the act itself, but because having no express desire for sexual activity will be disregarded due something as simple as your knickers, is disgusting .

i pick my clothing for me.
i pick my underwear because it makes me feel cute.
i dress in what is comfortable / clean.
some days i wear a plunging neckline.
some a turtle neck.
i wear yoga pants.
i wear slacks.
i dress to suit me.
i do not dress to be sexually assaulted! .

no one does! .

#thisisnotconsent #itsnotokay
#consentissexy #nomeansno #teachthemyoung #ibelieveher #ibelieveyou #metoo

text:
"i never had a reason to separate junot diaz from his art. in fact, so much of what made his art so true and so compelling was how much of him existed within it.  but much like my relationship with kanyeâ€™s work, continuing to show appreciation for it means questioning my morals."
this is an excerpt from a piece i wrote earlier this year titled, "when our heroes fail us" (link in bio).
-
back in may, news broke that pulitzer prize-winning author junot diaz had forcibly kissed a young female writer. he'd also displayed other forms of misogynistic behavior.  he's one of my literary heroes, and that disturbing news forced me to reconcile junot diaz the person with junot diaz the author. -
this week, the pulitzer board announced that diaz could remain a member after their investigation showed no evidence of wrongdoing. while i'm glad that he hasn't completely sabotaged his literary legacy, i have conflicted feelings. are we just supposed to pretend that these past incidents didn't happen? in this era of #metoo, how do we move forward when the accused is welcomed back into public favor?  how do you feel?
.

text:
revisiting my top 10: drive 
pt. 2/2
spoilers

another element i forgot and was delighted by was the aggressive use of fade transitions. scenes bleed into one another, giving us the feeling of a fugue state. itâ€™s as if weâ€™re reeling in goslingâ€™s pov right alongside him in the driverâ€™s seat (pun intended). gosling is an antihero, but heâ€™s distant from the criminals he drives and only kills and/or intimidates those who attack first. however...his true darkness surfaces when he slaps christina hendricks, pins her down, covers her mouth, and threatens to kill her. itâ€™s even more visceral  in the #metoo age. the act is a domestic terror we can relate to more than a curtain rod through a baddieâ€™s gullet. it borders on exploitation; willing to take the hero to a savage place that would definitely not be included today. 
thereâ€™s so much more to talk about. the orange/blue color palette. the framing. the allegorical motifs. the la setting. the driving scenes. the visceral yet sparse violence. ughhhsogood. 
overall, drive is mesmerizing, enchanting, and brutal. though heâ€™d gleefully polarize people with his next film, refn held the keys to everybodyâ€™s hearts and eyes in 2011, and forever changed the way i appreciate cinema. 
next up: moonlight

text:
i had the immense honor of seeing tarana burke speak a few weeks ago. she is the founder of the #metoo movement and has been working with victims of abuse for over 25 years.  when i tell you that woman knows her shitâ€” she knows her shit. sheâ€™s been in the trenches working to end sexual violence and abuse for years.
.
.
one of the things that most struck me was what she said about how to talk to people who are sharing their abuse with youâ€” she said the most powerful and healing thing you can say to them is â€œi believe youâ€. that you can create decades of healing with that one phrase.
.
.
it got me thinking of all kinds of abuse â€” not only sexual abuse. and how often when people share their abuse what they get instead is an intellectual nit picking. â€œare you sure that happened?â€ â€œwell that didnâ€™t happen to meâ€ â€œi think you must be misinterpreting the situationâ€”i doubt they would behave that wayâ€ â€œi donâ€™t believe everyone in the family is thinking or saying that to youâ€.

text:
thursday, december 06, 2018
4:00pmÂ toÂ 6:00pm â€œrevolutionary dreams and haitian girlhood"

rÃ©gine michelle jean-charlesÂ is a black feminist literary scholar and cultural critic specializing in francophone studies. her scholarship and teaching on world literatures in french includes work on black france, sub-saharan africa, haiti and the haitian diaspora. she is currently associate professor of romance languages and literatures and african and african diaspora studies at boston college. she holds a ba from the university of pennsylvania in french and african and african diaspora studies, and an am and phd in romance languages and literatures from harvard university.Â  she has received fellowships from the ford foundation, the mellon mays foundation and the woodrow wilson foundation.
her first book, conflict bodies:Â  the politics of rape representation in the francophone imaginary (columbus: ohio state university press, 2014) examines theoretical, visual, and literary texts that challenge the dominant views of sexual violence.Â  she has authored numerous scholarly articles that have appeared in edited volumes and peer-reviewed journals such as the journal of haitian studies, american quarterly, callaloo, french forum, journal of romance studies, research in african literatures, and small axe. her current research focuses on girlhood in contemporary haitian literature and visual culture. professor jean-charles serves as a board member of a long walk home, inc., a non-profit organization that uses art to educate, inspire, and mobilize young people to end violence against girls and women. she is also a regular contributor to media outlets like wgbh and cognoscenti, where she has weighed in on topics ranging from #metoo to issues affecting the haitian diaspora.

text:
this is my #metoo post, i've posted about this before, but not in much detail. 
today i had a phone call, it was the denver district attorney's office. i was informed my rapist is asking the judge that he not have to register as a sex offender anymore, since "he's had good behavior and done everything right". i learned a lot about my rapist today that i never knew, after the incident i was never told anything about what transpired in court, if he had been sentenced, nothing. i never had closure. i didn't how old he was, i either didn't know,  or had mentally blocked out his name, i only knew him by his nicknames "billy" or "snake", i hate that i was reminded, because now i feel completely screwed up and sick  inside. today i learned more about him than i cared to know. i guess i get to have an opinion about his request to the judge.  of course i don't feel comfortable with him not registering, no i dont think he should be allowed to not register. i don't even like the idea that he's still alive, that he was allowed medical care in prison to maintain his hiv, why not just let him fucking die?  why do prisoners get special treatment?  i had to get tested often before i was 18 to make sure i didn't contract that shit.  he drugged my cup of water, and eventually attacked me in a parking garage stairwell, (indoor closed stairwell). it was the last time i prayed to god, begged him outloud to make him stop, as he was over me telling me "oh you think your god is good?  that he will save you? i always wanted a young girl to love and now i'm fucking one" do you think he should be allowed not to register judge?  he doesnt look like how i remember,  he's obviously had his face smashed up during his time in prison. good i hope it was agonizing.  there are rapists everywhere,  watch your children and keep them close. for my colorado friends. this is his face. he may be your neighbor? he was released 5 years ago,  i had no idea!
#metoo #survivor  #sexoffendercolorado #sexoffender

text:
cw: sexual assault, verbal abuse. â €
â €
these past few months iâ€™ve been appalled at how sexual assault and abuse has been discussed in the media and even amongst friends and family. i find myself in conversations thinking, do they know it happened to me too? would they be saying this right now if they knew it did? sometimes i share that iâ€™m a survivor, if iâ€™m feeling brave. other times i sit in silence looking for an out so that i donâ€™t collapse into a puddle of panic. â €
â €
iâ€™ve spent the last two years in therapy sifting through how abuse and assault have effected my life. iâ€™ve realized that these experiences landed me in a position of using and abusing my own body. my body has felt like a battle field for so long, and finally in this last year or so i think iâ€™ve found peaceâ€¦ â €
â €
until these last few months when my attempts to block out related media werenâ€™t working anymore because the stories just hit too close to home. and then my body became a war zone againâ€¦ â €
â €
â€œsheâ€™s just saying these things for attentionâ€ - shots firedâ €
â€œwas she drinking?â€ - crumbling wallsâ €
â€œshe deserved itâ€ - bombs erupting throughout my bodyâ €
â €
did that mean i deserved it too? does that mean if iâ€™m honest about what happened that its just for attention? does this mean that every drunken night full of screaming and verbal abuse was my fault? iâ€™ve been struggling in this body again, and while i wonâ€™t blame anyone, i will say these comments are only helping to fuel the flames and give ammunition to my inner enemies. my body feels used and abused all over again every time i hear someone blame or ridicule a survivor. â €
â €
this post is to share a small glimpse of my story so that someone might rethink the next comments they make about assault or abuse. this post is for the person that needs to know theyâ€™re not alone. this post is not meant for action persay but rather a post for visibility and authenticity. because i believe these are the only ways we will make progress and build understanding. so i ask you merely to think, just think before you make a comment about assault or abuse that may be harmful. think before you add fuel to the fire of anothers war zoneâ €
#metoo #believesurvivors

text:
this is not my typical post.. taken on my phone. out of focus. and i did nothing to make this pretty. i personally didn't want to make this photo pretty. there is nothing pretty about it. 
i have struggled with whether i should share my #metoo experience for a long time. what good would it do? there will be backlash, and criticism i'm sure. my family will find out. and so far, i've told no one but ethan. however, this is a subject i am passionate about. and today, i had a conversation with someone who said "..my point was that we still realize the life we are part of such as there are neighborhoods i will not walk at night alone due to the danger... it is still my right but may not be safe. i know that if i got mugged people would blame me for walking in an area that this would happen at night. 
it is their fault and i would be the victim but i would think twice walking there again or what i would carry. prudence.." this was about wether a woman is truly asking for it when she walks around half naked. 
well. here is a small part of my story. this is what i was wearing the last time i was raped. mostly anyway. the same pair of jeans. except my drug rug what black and white. and i was wearing a hat.  the boy was older than me. taller than me. raised in a christian home and being trained for the air force. i had known him for months. i considered him a friend and trusted him. and i remember that night in all of it's terrible vivid detail. and with as hard as this is to put out there.. i'm going to. i was with one of my closest friends and a few others. and we we're drinking.. and when she left, he kissed me on the mouth. i backed away.. i didn't like it. he asked me to have sex. i said no. i said i wasn't comfortable with it. any girl who has ever been to a party knows that this then becomes the mans perogative to convince you. he continued to ask. to hang on me. i continued to say no. over. and over. at which point he picked me up and threw me on his bed. i pretended i was so drunk i passed out. and as i lay there hypersensitive to every fucking sense that i had he sat next to me and put his hand on my waist. he tried to kiss me. continued in comments.

text:
so iâ€™ve been mia because i was selected to be a juror last week... in a child sexual abuse case. needless to say i saw every right to drop off the face of the world and drink... heavily. .

i was intrigued by the process. it was something iâ€™d been curious about... whatâ€™s the process? how do they decide jurors ... how close is this to an episode of #suits or #lawandorder ? but the gravity set in quickly as i learned i was one of 12 out of 80 to be selected... well really our county holds 1/2 mil people sooo my odds were slim. . 
the case is done now so i can talk about it (thank god). as i learned of the details of the case i was struck by the severity of realizing i was going to be responsible for deciding who was â€œat faultâ€... an 8year old girl (now 12 testifying on the stand and who the defense is saying she lying ... bc.. children lie and want attention) or a 50 something year old man who by our legal standards innocent until proven guilty. i tried to put people i love in those seats to understand the decision in front of me. .
i drank every night. i cried every night. and even after the case has been done i went to yoga and cried as i sent my practice out to the girls who testified. .
i learned from one person who testified that she has interviewed 4k little girls in cases like these... 4,000k. iâ€™ve ran over the details of the case far too many times in my mind, iâ€™ve called my momma ruing , and woken from nightmares.
.
even still... i find myself trying to practice gratitude in this coming week that this case was put in my hands to follow my intuition, my heart, and the facts thatâ€™s the prosecution did their job to prove this man guilty. may these girls find peace, justice, and solitude in their lives and may the weight i now  carry lessen theirs. .

text:
to amanda kelly, 
global news and all montrealers. 
mom lied!! false allegations and perjury is a criminal offence.

mom did this knowing i would be detained in prison so that she could run off with my daughter.

she has done the same to the two previous fathers of her children.

i was never convicted. i got out of prison only to search for my daughter who is in danger with that woman.

my daughter was located in toronto and has inflicted harm. her half brother was sent to a children's hospital in toronto where mom was hiding under a different name. 
i have the right to defend myself and expose this madness that the laval police department intentionally neglected to investigate even after i've been begging them for help years before mom's lies.

there are no other victims, it never happened. the only victim is my daughter.

i was a great father to this little girl. she was happy here with me. mom needed to get rid of me and leave the province with my daughter. 
this case is now in two different provinces in family courts, criminal courts and civil court procedures. 
here is the link to the fake news article that was printed on me. october 28, 2014 (posted below). i strongly suggest the journalist that printed that without doing any research of his/her own to take it down. 
mom is going to jail. 
remember my words. 
children have been hurt and families destroyed by one woman's lies and violence. it took her two minuets to make a call and do all this damage but it's taking me over four years to be heard. see the difference? 
signed...stephanos chrysanthe svourenos

text:
every witch practices with their own code of ethics, just like everyone else. we all have good and bad in us, darkness and light. the most powerful witches i met know that you need to acknowledge both sides of yourself and your experiences, finding balance. âš”ï¸ some witches refuse to work magick on others, some only do so with consent, some only for justice. i met witches who hex serial rapists, seeking recourse where our patriarchal criminal justice system - designed to benefit men - continues to fail women. others will use their powers however they want. every witch has their reasons behind their ethical approach. 
witchcraft ethics are rooted in a belief in whatâ€™s called the three fold law, which states that any energy you put out into the world will come back on you tenfold. magickal karma, if you will. ğŸŒ€not all witches believe in the law, but those who do often do so because theyâ€™ve learned the hard way. hex someone or practice powerful dark magic, and itâ€™ll result in chronic illness, job loss, your house burning down, or the death of a loved one. not today, not tomorrow, but itâ€™ll catch up to you eventually. 
witch or not, if we all acted in respect of the three fold law, we would be a hell of a lot nicer to one another. because â€œa hex always comes for its pound of flesh,â€ as one witch told me. unless you donâ€™t believe in the law. ğŸ˜‰

photo taken at a ritual hex on supreme court justice brett kavanaugh at @catlandbooks. witches gathered to hex him, trump, and mitch mcconnell using these poppets. poppets are dolls used as proxies for the spellâ€™s targets as is common in conjure, voodoo, hoodoo, vodou, and other witchcraft practices common to the south. after the ritual hex, the witches held a second ritual to honor survivors of sexual assault (nearly everyone in the room, myself included). because as weâ€™ve learned in the #metoo movement, justice is a  necessary element of healing. âœŠğŸ¼ shot for my ongoing project on the intersectionality of contemporary witchcraft. more in bio.

words cannot express how devastated i am and hundreds more are about the recent sexual assault and rape case in ireland. 
a 17 year old girl was allegedly raped in ireland, but has since committed suicide since her trial. during the trial, the defence lawyer told the jury, â€œyou have to look at the way she was dressed. she was wearing a thong with a lace front." never should someone be raped or sexually assaulted because of the clothes they wear. this is unacceptable behaviour from the man who allegedly raped her and his defence team. because of this a smart, kind, and exceptional girl lost her life. 
how many more girls have to be sexually assaulted and raped before these terrible people stop? 
#thisisnotconsent #timesup #metoo #wewantavoice #wewillbeheard #timesneedtochange #nomorebs

text:
our first â€˜women for change run/walkâ€™ was initiated as an ad-hoc event and a direct reaction to the dramatic events unfolding in march 2016. 
within one week cape town was shocked by the brutal murders of several teen girls across the city. as the largest all-women running community we had to take a stand to protest the violence against women and children in south africa.

looking back, it hasn't changed much. everyday we have children and women being attacked, raped and murdered.  abuse against women and children is an epidemic in this country. something we have to overcome now! 
let's unite and stand as one to protect our wonderful children and women. let's keep on claiming our public spaces back. let's continue to spread love, because together we are the change. let's do it now! 
stand with us united in sandton city on the 1st december during 16 days of activism. 
#womenforchange #sisterhood #together #metoo #16daysofactivism #timesup #women #thetotalshutdown #spreadlove #changetheworld #girlpower

text:
our first â€˜women for change run/walkâ€™ was initiated as an ad-hoc event and a direct reaction to the dramatic events unfolding in march 2016. 
within one week cape town was shocked by the brutal murders of several teen girls across the city. as the largest all-women running community we had to take a stand to protest the violence against women and children in south africa.

looking back, it hasn't changed much. everyday we have children and women being attacked, raped and murdered.  abuse against women and children is an epidemic in this country. something we have to overcome now! 
let's unite and stand as one to protect our wonderful children and women. let's keep on claiming our public spaces back. let's continue to spread love, because together we are the change. let's do it now! 
stand with us united in sandton city on the 1st december during 16 days of activism. 
#womenforchange #sisterhood #together #metoo #16daysofactivism #timesup #women #thetotalshutdown #spreadlove #changetheworld #girlpower

text:
people always want to know how to stay sober and for me it's all about incorporating wellness proactively to keep my energy at a high vibration. when i am balanced in mind, body and spirit i have no desire to drink or binge on sugary treats. 
i keep track of it all by using my daily wellness tool that my brother and i created. 
the outside pentagon represents the five core pillars that we realized kept us hydrated, well rested and helped us lose weight! they are all free and anyone can do them everyday for wellness 
the inside triangle are personal preference extra credits for achieving goals. for general balance do one thing everyday for mind body and spirit.  for body transformation do three things for your body like yoga, hiking or a boxing class. i also used it for debt pay off and career growth ğŸ’°
this little system is shockingly effective when done everyday and helps me focus on small daily change!

text:
this can happen all too easily. with our partners, with our children. we care so much we forget to put ourselves first.

but what gets done if you don't take care of number one? nothing. just like putting on oxygen when the plane is going down, they always instruct you to put your own on first.

and without oxygen we're all fucked lol.

dont ever lose yourself.

itâ€™s just sad the world we are living in, we may not be able to change the world, but we can reduce the suffering of one another by being there. share your stories with people you trust, it might not cure the pain but it will help you heal faster.

text:
broadly speaking, there are three core elements to #metoo, writes cristy clark:

1. the sheer volume of disclosures highlights that sexual harassment and abuse are unacceptably widespread â€“ and that institutions and society at large are failing to protect and support victims. 
2. the practice of using the hashtag to challenge the stigma and shame that has somehow accompanied identifying as a victim. 
3. the fact some disclosures on twitter have sought to name and shame perpetrators of abuse in order to seek accountability and justice.
.
read more here: 
https://theconversation.com/metoo-exposes-legal-failures-but-trial-by-twitter-isnt-one-of-them-92683

text:
cw: sexual violence, army / military brutality

instances of sexual violence live on in cultural memory in different ways. in 'the last song' temsula ao writes the story of apenyo, a young naga woman who was subjected to gang-rape and murdered, along with her mother, by the indian army. in the story, the army decides to visit the village and arrest all leaders for their 'crime' of paying taxes to underground forces â€”something the villagers were compelled to do. incensed by apenyo and the villagers' defiance the soldiers shoot, kick and club those trying to escape or seek shelter in the old church. the captain who leads the rapes sees villagers trying help the two women, and orders soldiers to surround the church and empty their guns into it, after which it is set on fire. the new church too, along with granaries and houses catch the blaze. the villagers are threatened not to spread the news of what had happened there.

afterwards, as the villagers recoup their losses, it is decided after much debate that as per old traditions, deaths from 'unnatural' causes could not be buried in the village graveyard. as a compromise mother and daughter are buried just outside the boundary of the graveyard to show that their fellow villagers had not abandoned them. but no headstones are erected. the story ends with the two gravesites as unmarked grassy knolls whose story lives on in the souls of those who survived the darkest day of the village some thirty odd years ago.

apenyo is a fictional stand-in for real women affected by army #impunity in areas such as the #northeast affected by #afspa.

what do you make of apenyo's actions and how do you respond to her story? what can resistance or '#justice' look like in these complex situations? what are some stories of resistance that you have heard?

#zubaanbooks #exitimpunity #sexualviolence #endsexualviolence #metoo #metooindia #smashbrahminicalpatriarchy #feminist #feministart #womensrights #feministpractice #genderbasedviolence #resistance #racism

text:
every individual has there own experiences as a child.. someone has good memories and someone has bad/worst. as a parent i discuss with my children about good touch and bad touch, how to be safe and what to be done if something/ someone is bad. 
i would like to ask every parent who read my message to discuss with their children (girl/boy) about good and bad touch. this is the first step to make them understand what is right and wrong. 
i always wanted to support and help children to be mentally strong. so i have chosen my platform to educate children about child abuse and also teach them how to protect them from the abuser.

stay tuned to @swechalaya to know how to protect our children from abuse!!
share your thoughts and experiences to swechalaya@gmail@com. we are here to support you and help you.  #swechalaya #protectchildfromabuse #childabuse #childabuseawareness #childabusesurvivor #childprotectionservices #childabuseprevention #childabusevictims #keepchildrensafe #lovechildhood #futuregeneration #protectfuturegenerations #abuseawareness #helpchildren #ourchildren #trustyourchild #metoo

text:
let's form a network of people volunteering for those who need help. this is not an organization, this is not a distress app service but just a cause to make this city feel secure. we need to kill the patriarchal mindset of bullies and ignorant mindsets. a vision to see this city as:
parents and family shall be carefree if a woman from their family is outside the house regardless of time.

don't stay quiet, raise your voice. even if it's stalking, a bad touch, visual harassment or anything for that matter, it must be exposed and raise voice against.
dm for more.

#women #india #newdelhi #indianfeminism #womensafety #metoo #metoomovement #molestation #harassment #feminist #womenempowerment #patriarchy

i am truly thankful for being healthy enough this year to experience the beauty of autumn in east tennessee. october is my favorite month for sunrises, sunsets, and our changing leaves. the last few years had left me unable to appreciate these things. in october 2013, i was hospitalized on a 6 month bedrest, and facing leg amputation due to a severe mrsa infection following surgery to remove a large tumor. in october 2014, i was in and out of the hospital with brain swelling and seizures following a car accident. in october 2015, i was in an intensive outpatient dbt class, being diagnosed with an ed, and doing everything i possibly could to pass myself off as fine and avoid hospitalization. in october 2016, i was relapsing hard with the drinking and my ed. in 2017, my ptsd symptoms were triggered by the #metoo movement and i relapsed very quickly and very dangerously with my ed. i pretty much stopped functioning. honestly, i don't know how i survived that one. this summer, all my mental illnesses have hit me hard, harder than ever before, and all at once. all. at. once. but i fought, and continue to fight, harder than i ever have in my entire life. and that was how i was able to enjoy the beautiful colors of autumn this year. and i'm glad they waited until november because october was pretty tough for me. again, i'm extremely thankful for those who continue to support me and love me during the times when doing so is rather difficult.
#rawrecovery 
#thankful 
#autumn

text:
an honest and sad perspective on how to deal with the growing alcohol issue. the reality is that the majority of our lawmakers drink and profit from the alcohol addiction epidemic. no one seems to care though because the lives of alcoholic people are not valuable to society. we view this population as lacking willpower and weak, we don't even attempt to protect them from the aggressive advertising and marketing of the drug that kills them. 
they have no incentive to make changes. i dated a lobbyist for the republican party and he agreed there was zero chance of things changing with the current people in office because they are all high functioning alcoholics. he was as well and had zero interest in quitting, despite knowing he was harming himself and his children. he said he would lose his job, his friends, etc. he acted like i was crazy to get help after a missed meeting. told me i was ridiculous and dramatic and his friends covered for him, they all miss tons of meetings because of drinking and accept it as normal. when that's happening no one is speaking up for the alcoholic people and the benefits of sobriety. 
for certain reasons alcohol is deemed acceptable and we blame the individual in pain for becoming addicted rather than take a hard look at this dangerous drug and make changes to the current approach. 
it's my belief that alcohol is different from smoking and will be much harder to change the way we view alcohol. 
many men use alcohol to get laid and therefore are never going to be interested in women drinking less. this came from my brother and therapist, also a man, they told me the truth. cigarettes never benefited men like alcohol does. 
men make the laws in this country so let's not hold our breath waiting for things to change. women need to be the ones to quit drinking on their own, the government is not going to be supporting this movement, they benefit from keeping us addicted ğŸ‡ºğŸ‡¸ğŸ˜¥ #godry #drydiet #godry #healthyandwealthy #sober #weightlossjourney #transformation #empoweringwomen #nohangover #noalcohol #metoo #mentalhealth #teetotaler #sober #nohangover

text: iâ€™ve been thinking quite a bit about when to attach my face and name to @bossladycreates. iâ€™ve never intended for this to be anonymous. i have nothing to hide. in my every day life, iâ€™ll tell my story to *anyone* who will listen, and i want other survivors to be as unashamed to share their experiences as i am. when i started this account, i think i had so much to say that introductions and selfies kind of fell by the wayside; and now that iâ€™m thinking about it, i know that thereâ€™s no â€œgoodâ€ time for anything- all of it is just a leap i have to take. iâ€™m in brooklyn right now, connecting and networking with other survivors on an incredible project spearheaded by one of my very best friends (side note: what weâ€™re creating is extraordinary, and i cannot wait to share it with this fellow survivor community...). iâ€™ve brought some of my leaves with me, and as iâ€™m sitting in her bedroom typing this, in the corner of her dresser mirror are two stickers: â€œbadass feministâ€ and â€œyou are beautiful.â€ i love knowing that when she wakes up in the morning and first looks at herself, these words appear alongside her gorgeous face as a daily reminder of her power and strength. and she absolutely is both of those things: a badass feminist and beautiful. now that iâ€™m seeing my own reflection here, i know that theyâ€™re true for me, too. so this is my introduction: my name is mel. iâ€™m a survivor. iâ€™m a badass feminist. i am beautiful. itâ€™s so nice to finally meet you all!âœ¨ #survivor #selfie #survivoradvocate #believesurvivors #believewomen #metoo #timesup #endrapeculture #badassfeminist #iambeautiful #artist #wip

rÃ©gine michelle jean-charlesÂ is a black feminist literary scholar and cultural critic specializing in francophone studies. her scholarship and teaching on world literatures in french includes work on black france, sub-saharan africa, haiti and the haitian diaspora. she is currently associate professor of romance languages and literatures and african and african diaspora studies at boston college. she holds a ba from the university of pennsylvania in french and african and african diaspora studies, and an am and phd in romance languages and literatures from harvard university.Â  she has received fellowships from the ford foundation, the mellon mays foundation and the woodrow wilson foundation.
her first book, conflict bodies:Â  the politics of rape representation in the francophone imaginary (columbus: ohio state university press, 2014) examines theoretical, visual, and literary texts that challenge the dominant views of sexual violence.Â  she has authored numerous scholarly articles that have appeared in edited volumes and peer-reviewed journals such as the journal of haitian studies, american quarterly, callaloo, french forum, journal of romance studies, research in african literatures, and small axe. her current research focuses on girlhood in contemporary haitian literature and visual culture. professor jean-charles serves as a board member of a long walk home, inc., a non-profit organization that uses art to educate, inspire, and mobilize young people to end violence against girls and women. she is also a regular contributor to media outlets like wgbh and cognoscenti, where she has weighed in on topics ranging from #metoo to issues affecting the haitian diaspora.

so how do we prevent religion or belief discrimination?
talk to each other.
the festive season is in full swing and organisations debate whether or not to deck the office halls and whether to even utter the c-word â€“ christmas â€“ for fear of offence or reprisal. organisations need to understand, appreciate and be sensitive to the beliefs of their employees, but most importantly talk to your people, cultivate that culture of openness and respect.
indeed, the very assumption of offence due to someoneâ€™s religion or beliefs can itself be offensive and may inadvertently lead to further isolation and marginalisation.
concerned by the reception of a dress code, policies relating to leave/holiday, working patterns and flexible working, or whether to mark certain religious holidays or traditional celebrations? ask your people what they think.  #gurls #workplace #woman #entrepreneur #femaleentrepreneur
